When I saw this, I *Immediately* thought of my two diving buddies, Jay Strifler and Peter Bihun > The things they used to do to each other, pranks, practical jokes, drunken fights...etc. Their antics over the years were a constant source of 'laugh til it hurts' entertainment that none of us ever seemed to tire of witnessing. It was just one jawdropping moment after the next. Tnx for the memories guys!

    Share on Your Timeline

    Still think of Peter Bihun and Jay-jon Strifler almost daily. A brief smile always follows as I reminiscence at the fun we had and the trouble we got into.

    For many years, Jay, Peter and myself traveled Countries together, as members of an elite Professional World High Diving Team (actually, all of us were employed by various smaller companies, but most of the time we worked for the best shows at the best theme parks in the WORLD! And ALL we had to do in order to be a true brother in our elite worldwide class of the best high divers in the world, was to chuck a couple of big dives such as arm stand two-and=a=half, half, or a mid-turning triple, split reverse double.

    Never officially recorded, I estimate that in the 9 years I spent on the had apx 3000 high dives from above 85 feet (exactly measured, not just a guess) We were all good at what we did, and the rewards were far more valuable than the money - we were the boys who still get talked about in the High Diving World. We made memories that would become legacies for high divers now, 30 years later...

    A real perk of the job was that where ever we went (LA, Toronto, Texas, Florida, Massachusetts, , we really got to experience the culture and the people we met wherever that road took us really allowed us to meet the people cause they all wanted to meet us. One guy had a Riverboat in London and Jay talked him into giving us a full tour through London. Went through multiple locks lifting or dropping us a good 12-15 feet each time, both ways - sailed past the Tower Of London and finally U-Turned when the sun started setting.

    In my memory I recall it being about 4-5 hours of actual 'sea time' over the period of about 10 full hours - left in the morning, back late at night. We the Temmes River sailed for about 4 hours total over a 10-12 hour day of just FUN FUN FUN! I'd guess we sailed (The rest of the time was spent going alongside every River Themes . af the years we spent traveling Countries together!! smile every time.
